  <fr:p>Having a bottom element and being an algebra are both <fr:em>properties</fr:em> of dcpos, because these structures are uniquely determined. Therefore, we will argue that <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-001S.xml"
addr="jms-001S"
title="Pointed dcpo">pointed dcpos</fr:link> with bottom-preserving morphisms form the same <fr:em>subcategory</fr:em> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {dcpo}]]></fr:tex> as the category of algebras with algebra-preserving maps. We have already seen that pointed structure and algebra structure are interchangeable:</fr:p>

  <fr:ol><fr:li><fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-001T.xml"
addr="jms-001T"
title="Pointed dcpos are lift-algebras">Pointed dcpos are lift-algebras</fr:link></fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-001V.xml"
addr="jms-001V"
title="Lift-algebras are pointed">Lift-algebras are pointed</fr:link></fr:li></fr:ol>


  <fr:p>To finish, we recall that a morphism of dcpos <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-001X.xml"
addr="jms-001X"
title="Bottom-preserving maps vs. algebra morphisms">preserves algebra structure if and only if it preserves the bottom element</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
